 position in a highly unequal society. As the distance between rich and poor widens, Uneasy Street not only explores the lives of those at the top but also sheds light on how extreme inequality comes to seem ordinary and acceptable to the rest of us.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aRich peoplezUnited States. 0aSocial classeszUnited States. 0aSocial stratificationzUnited States. 0aWealthzUnited States. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Social Classes & Economic Disparity.2bisacsh  aAdvertising.  aAfrican Americans.  aAllusion.  aAmbivalence.  aAwareness.  aBabysitting.  aBehalf.  aCareer.  aChild care.  aClothing.  aCommunity service.  aCompetition.  aConcierge.  aConspicuous consumption.  aConsumer.  aConsumption (economics).  aCultural capital.  aDebt.  aDisadvantage.  aDomestic worker.  aEconomic inequality.  aEconomics.  aEgalitarianism.  aEmployment.  aEntitlement.  aEntrepreneurship.  aEric Klinenberg.  aEuphemism.  aExpense.  aFinance.  aFurniture.  aGrandparent.  aGrocery store.  aHandbag.  aHis Family.  aHousehold income.  aHousehold.  aHousewife.  aIncome distribution.  aIncome.  aInstitution.  aInterior design.  aInterview.  aJuliet Schor.  aLaundry.  aLegitimation.  aLifestyle management.  aLuxury goods.  aMeritocracy.  aMiddle class.  aMoney management.  aMy Child.  aNarrative.  aNest Egg.  aNet worth.  aNew York University.  aNonprofit organization.  aNorm (social).  aObligation.  aOrganization.  aParenting.  aPercentage.  aPersonal assistant.  aPersonhood.  aPhilanthropy.  aPolitician.  aPopular culture.  aPrivate school.  aPublic Knowledge.  aPuritans.  aReal estate appraisal.  aReal estate broker.  aRelative deprivation.  aRenovation.  aReproductive labor.  